# The problem
## dark variant usage

It's very easy to declare a custom
```
dark
```
variant to customize dark mode detection, as showed in the beta docs :

```
@variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *)); /* <body class="dark"> */
@variant dark (&:where([data-theme="dark"], [data-theme="dark"] *); /* <body data-theme="dark"> */
```

…

## CSS variables usage

This is sadly not the case if you are working with CSS variables, instead of relying on the
```
dark
```
variant.

Your config would most likely look like something like this (see #14091 & #14095) :

```
:root {
  --text-fg: #000;

  :where(.dark) {
    --text-fg: #fff;
  }
}

/* `inline` is necessary to make it work */
@theme inline {
  --color-fg: var(--text-fg);
}
```

…

A potential solution could look like this :
```
/* Step 1: define your `dark` mode variant */
@variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));

/* Step 2: define your color values, independently from the detection logic */
@variations {
  --text-fg: #000; /* this would be the default value */

  @dark {
    --text-fg: #fff; /* this would be the value when the dark mode variant selector matches the element */
  }
}

/* Step 3: define your theme colors as usual */
@theme inline {
  --color-fg: var(--text-fg);
}
```

